data.content:
## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### Why this breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` ŌĆö it simply doesn't work. `ThreadAbortException` is never raised, and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`). You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** with `CancellationToken`.

---

### Pattern analysis of your code

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow for cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

---

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work ŌĆö same logic as the old
                // ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed ŌĆö OperationCanceledException does
                // NOT auto-rethrow. The loop condition exits naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(2000));

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Key changes to `GetNextItem`

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue or I/O), it **must** accept the token ŌĆö otherwise cancellation stalls until the blocking call returns on its own:

```csharp
// BEFORE ŌĆö blocks indefinitely, can't be cancelled
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until item available
}

// AFTER ŌĆö wakes up immediately on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If it uses `Thread.Sleep`, replace that too:

```csharp
// BEFORE
Thread.Sleep(1000);

// AFTER ŌĆö wakes on cancellation instead of sleeping the full duration
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000);
```

---

### Critical pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Not passing the token to `GetNextItem`** | The thread stays blocked indefinitely ŌĆö `Cancel()` has no effect until the call returns. This is the #1 migration mistake. |
| **Using `Thread.Sleep` in the wait** | Your original `Stop()` used `Thread.Sleep(2000)`. Use `Thread.Join(timeout)` instead ŌĆö it actually waits for the thread to finish rather than just burning time. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` is `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. Always dispose after use. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one from inner code. |
| **Assuming cancellation is immediate** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` runs for 30 seconds without checking the token, cancellation waits that long. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside long operations. |

---

### `Thread.ResetAbort` ŌĆö why it just disappears

In .NET Framework, `ThreadAbortException` auto-rethrew at the end of the catch block unless `ResetAbort()` was called. `OperationCanceledException` has **no auto-rethrow behavior** ŌĆö once caught, it stays caught. So `ResetAbort` simply has no equivalent and no need for one. The `finally` block runs normally either way.
